name: Suivre les modifications du workflow n8n au fil du temps avec Compare Dataset & Google Sheets
description:
### Ce modèle n8n s'exécute quotidiennement pour suivre et rapporter les modifications apportées aux workflows sur n'importe quelle instance n8n.

Utile si une équipe travaille au sein d'une seule instance et que vous souhaitez être informé des workflows qui ont changé depuis votre dernière visite. Un autre cas d'utilisation pourrait être la surveillance de vos instances gérées pour des clients et d'être alerté lorsque des modifications sont apportées sans votre connaissance.

Voir un exemple de Gsheet ici : [https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1dOHSfeE0W_qPyEWj5Zz0JBJm8Vrf_cWp-02OBrA_ZYc/edit?usp=sharing](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1dOHSfeE0W_qPyEWj5Zz0JBJm8Vrf_cWp-02OBrA_ZYc/edit?usp=sharing)

### Comment ça fonctionne
* Un déclencheur programmé est configuré pour s'exécuter une fois par jour afin de passer en revue tous les workflows disponibles.
* Un nœud n8n importe les workflows au format json.
* Les workflows sont intégrés dans une boucle où chacun est d'abord vérifié pour voir s'il existe dans la feuille Google désignée.
* Si ce n'est pas le cas, une nouvelle entrée est créée et ignorée.
* Si le workflow a déjà été capturé, alors le sous-workflow de comparaison peut être exécuté en utilisant les versions précédente et actuelle des données json du workflow.
* Le sous-workflow utilise l'outil de comparaison de jeux de données pour calculer les changements apportés aux nœuds et aux connexions pour le workflow donné.
* Les résultats sont ensuite enregistrés dans la feuille Google pour révision.

### Comment utiliser
* Commencez par le nœud n8n et essayez de filtrer par les workflows qui vous intéressent pour le suivi.
* Définissez l'intervalle de déclenchement programmé pour correspondre à la fréquence à laquelle vos workflows sont modifiés.

### Personnalisation du workflow
* Vous voulez être créatif ? Ajoutez un agent IA pour aider à déterminer les changements entre les versions précédente et actuelle du workflow. Ajoutez des explications contextuelles pour révéler l'impact des changements.

parameters.content:
## 1. Get Workflows To Track
[Learn more about the n8n node](https://docs.n8n.io/integrations/builtin/core-nodes/n8n-nodes-base.n8n/)

To start, we'll need the json templates of the workflows that exist in the n8n instance. We can easily get these by using the n8n node. You may want to further filter down workflow depending on which ones you want to track.

## 2. Create GSheet Entry If Workflow is New
[Read more about the loop node](https://docs.n8n.io/integrations/builtin/core-nodes/n8n-nodes-base.splitinbatches)

Next, we'll need to determine which workflows are currently new vs already being tracked. This is important as we can only compare workflow versions if we have a previous copy of it. If a workflow doesn't have an entry in our sheet then we can presume it's new and no comparison is necessary as of yet.

## 3. Calculate Changes Since Last Update
[Read more about the Execute Workflow node](https://docs.n8n.io/integrations/builtin/core-nodes/n8n-nodes-base.executeworkflow/)

If a previous version exists, we'll can compare it with the current versions to workout what exactly has changed. Here, I'll pass both versions of the workflow's json to a subworkflow which can compare the two.

## 5. Update GSheet Entry with Changes
[Read more about the Google Sheets node](https://docs.n8n.io/integrations/builtin/app-nodes/n8n-nodes-base.googlesheets)

The resulting list of changes of the workflow are updated in the Google sheet for review. From here, it's possible to connect messaging and/or notification platforms to alert on changes which may break the business processes or worse!

## 4. Calculate Differences in Nodes & Connections
[Learn more about the Compare Datasets node](https://docs.n8n.io/integrations/builtin/core-nodes/n8n-nodes-base.comparedatasets)

Our comparison focuses on changes between nodes and connections. It does this by running both the previous and current versions of the workflow json through the "Compare dataset" node to find the differences. Using this node, we're able to determine how many nodes and/or connections were added or removed.

## Try It Out!
### This n8n template runs daily to track and report on any changes to available workflows on an n8n instance.

Useful if a team is working within a single instance and you want to be notified of what workflows have changed since you last visited them. Another use-case might be monitoring your managed instances for clients and being alerted when changes are made without your knowledge.

See a sample Gsheet here: [https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1dOHSfeE0W_qPyEWj5Zz0JBJm8Vrf_cWp-02OBrA_ZYc/edit?usp=sharing](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1dOHSfeE0W_qPyEWj5Zz0JBJm8Vrf_cWp-02OBrA_ZYc/edit?usp=sharing)

### How it works
* A scheduled trigger is set to run once a day to review all available workflows.
* An n8n node imports the workflows as json.
* The workflows are brought into a loop where each is first checked to see if it exists in the designated google sheet.
* If not, a new entry is created and skipped.
* If the workflow has been captured before, then the comparison subworkflow can be executed using the previous and current versions of the workflow json data.
* The subworkflow uses the compare dataset tool to calculate the changes to nodes and connections for the given workflow.
* The results are then recorded back to the google sheet for review.

### How to use
* Start with the n8n node and try to filter by the workflows you're interested in tracking.
* Set the scheduled trigger interval to match the frequency to suit how often your workflows are being edited.

### Need Help?
Join the [Discord](https://discord.com/invite/XPKeKXeB7d) or ask in the [Forum](https://community.n8n.io/)!

Happy Hacking!

data.details:
The IF node can be used to implement binary conditional logic in your workflow. You can set up one-to-many conditions to evaluate each item of data being inputted into the node. That data will either evaluate to TRUE or FALSE and route out of the node accordingly.

This node has multiple types of conditions: Bool, String, Number, and Date & Time.
